''Backbreaker'' received mixed reviews from critics. While it was praised for its realistic physics, it was also criticized for weak online play, lack of single-player gameplay depth, and poor passing play.<ref name="ign"/><ref name="psl"/><ref name="kotaku"/>  Review aggregator [[Metacritic]] rated the game at 54% for the Xbox 360 version and 58% for the PlayStation 3 version, calling it "a fast-paced, gritty gameplay experience that's more Burnout than Madden,".<ref name="mc360">{{cite web|title=Backbreaker|url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/xbox360/backbreaker?q=backbreaker|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=24 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="meta" <ref name="meta">{{cite web|title=Backbreaker (PS3)|url=http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Backbreaker_(video_game)&action=submit|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref> ''Backbreaker'' also received an aggregate score of 57.31% on [[GameRankings]], based upon 21 different media reviews.<ref name="gamrnk">{{cite web|title=GameRankings: ''Backbreaker''|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xbox360/942984-backbreaker/index.html|publisher=[[GameRankings]]|accessdate=24 July 2010}}</ref> The game's [[Euphoria]] physics system was well-liked by reviewers. PlayStation LifeStyle's Joseph Patterson commented that "Realism is a major plus in Backbreaker. Running with the ball feels lifelike and better than any other football game on the market...The fact that the game really tries to make you feel what the player is feeling is probably the game<U+2019>s crowning achievement...literally every tackle is completely different,"<ref name="psl"/> while Jay Acevedo of GameFocus added "...while the game does not scream perfection, it delivers the promise of a realistic and exhilarating experience," in his review.<ref name="gf"/> 

Although developers billed a realistic atmosphere, reviewers criticized that aspect of the game. "I understand the emphisis for this game is on the gameplay. However, a little more effort could have been made with the visuals and particularly in the audio department. Crowds will applaud your great plays and touchdowns, but the essence of a football game revolves around atmosphere. Here, it<U+2019>s completely lacking," said Acevedo in his review.<ref name="gf"/> The game was also criticized for it's lack of play-by-play and poor audio.<ref name="gf"/> "There's no witty banter between a play-by-play announcer and color commentator (although some would argue that Madden's audio presentation's been seriously lacking the past few iterations), there's no stadium music aside from <U+201C>[[Boom (P.O.D. song)|Boom]]<U+201D> by [[P.O.D.]] being played during kickoffs (it gets old pretty fast), and the stadium crowds are basically an afterthought," added Doug Aamoth of Techland.<ref name="techland">{{cite news|last=Aamoth|first=Doug|title=Backbreaker Review: It's No Madden, But Maybe That's Okay|url=http://techland.com/2010/06/10/backbreaker-review-its-no-madden-but-maybe-thats-okay/|accessdate=24 July 2010|publisher=Techland|date=10 June 2010}}</ref>

''Backbreaker'''s close "on the field" camera was also panned by critics. "Because the camera places you right on the field, all of the hits carry even more weight than if you were zoomed farther back, but the positive aspects are overshadowed by an inability to see the entire field," said [[Gamespot]]'s review of ''Backbreaker'', while [[GameZone]] added that "Backbreaker uses a tight third-person view that brings the player closer to the action. The results are visually interesting, but the mechanics are mismanaged. While the game strives to be as simple and as straightforward as possible, the camera often gets in the way."<ref name="gs">{{cite news|title=Backbreaker Review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/sports/backbreaker/review.html|accessdate=25 July 2010|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref name="gamezone">{{cite news|last=Bedigian|first=Louis|title=Backbreaker Review|url=http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/item/backbreaker_review/|accessdate=25 July 2010|publisher=GameZone|date=4 June 2010}}</ref>

The game was nominated for Best New IP at the 2010 Develop Awards,<ref name="dev">{{cite news|last=French|first=Michael|title=Develop Awards: the finalists are revealed|url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/34998/Develop-Awards-the-finalists-are-revealed|accessdate=25 July 2010|publisher=Develop Online|date=3 June 2010}}</ref> but lost to [[Quantic Dream]]'s [[Heavy Rain]].<ref name="nextgen">{{cite news|last=Ivan|first=Tom|title=Quantic Dream And Rocksteady Scoop Develop Awards|url=http://www.next-gen.biz/news/quantic-dream-and-rocksteady-scoop-develop-awards|accessdate=25 July 2010|newspaper=Next-Gen|date=15 July 2010}}</ref>

''Backbreaker'''s mobile editions fared well, selling over 1.5 million copies of their application.<ref name="ipad"/> The iPhone and Android versions also received positive reviews from critics. "Backbreaker is a fun mini game with cool graphics and animations," said Eli Hodapp in his review of the application. "There isn't anything overly technical about the gameplay, but it has a strangely compelling aspect to it, especially as you're high stepping to the end zone," he added.<ref name="ta">{{cite web|last=Hodapp|first=Eli|title='Backbreaker Football: Tackle Alley' Review|url=http://toucharcade.com/2009/09/22/backbreaker-football-tackle-alley-preview-with-gameplay-video/|publisher=Touch Arcade|accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref>

